Case Study: Is Spotify’s Profitability Sustainable?
Hypothesis: Spotify’s profitability is fragile. Revenue growth is driven by volume not pricing power and faces a natural ceiling. Meanwhile ~60% of Q1 2026 net profit came from one-off items, not core operations.
Revenue Analysis (Price × Volume)
	•	Total revenue: €4.53B (+8% YoY)
	•	Users grew 12% but revenue only grew 8% — users are growing faster than revenue
	•	ARPU: €4.76, roughly flat — Spotify is not extracting more value per user
	•	Premium (91% of revenue): €4.15B (+10%) — healthy but volume-driven
	•	Ads (9% of revenue): €385M (−5%) — shrinking, not a viable growth engine
Cost & Profit Analysis (Fixed + Variable)
	•	Gross margin: 33% (record high) — looks healthy
	•	Operating income: €715M (+40%)
	•	Net income: €721M — but €438M came from a tax benefit and finance income
	•	Conclusion: ~60% of net profit was inflated by one-off items
Conclusion
Spotify’s profitability is real at the operating level but fragile at the net income level. The core business is improving, but the headline profit number is misleading. Long term sustainability depends on improving ARPU, not just adding users.
Recommendation
Spotify should introduce tiered pricing to directly fix the flat ARPU problem. Three tiers: an ad-lite tier (below current premium, reduced ads, full features like free song selection and unlimited skips) to convert free users who won’t pay full price; the current premium as the standard middle tier; and a super-premium tier with lossless audio and AI-powered features targeting power users. Family plans across all three tiers. This grows both the paying user base and average revenue per user without relying on volume growth alone.
Source: Spotify Technology S.A., Q1 2026 Earnings Report (Form 6-K), April 28 2026.
